ðŸŒ¿ 1. map() in Java
Definition:

map() is used to transform each element of a stream into another form.

It performs a one-to-one mapping.

Syntax:
<R> Stream<R> map(Function<? super T, ? extends R> mapper)

Key Point:

âž¡ Each element of the stream is mapped to exactly one new element.

Example â€“ map()
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Atul", "Ramesh", "Suresh");

List<Integer> nameLengths = names.stream()
                                 .map(String::length)
                                 .toList();

System.out.println(nameLengths);


Output:

[4, 6, 6]


âœ… Here:

"Atul" â†’ 4

"Ramesh" â†’ 6

"Suresh" â†’ 6

Each input element maps to exactly one output element.

ðŸŒŠ 2. flatMap() in Java
Definition:

flatMap() is used to flatten nested structures (like lists of lists) and then apply mapping.

It performs a one-to-many mapping.

Syntax:
<R> Stream<R> flatMap(Function<? super T, ? extends Stream<? extends R>> mapper)

Key Point:

âž¡ Each element of the stream is mapped to a Stream, and then all resulting streams are flattened into a single stream.

Example â€“ flatMap()
List<List<String>> namesList = Arrays.asList(
    Arrays.asList("Atul", "Ramesh"),
    Arrays.asList("Suresh", "Mahesh")
);

List<String> allNames = namesList.stream()
                                 .flatMap(List::stream)
                                 .toList();

System.out.println(allNames);


Output:

[Atul, Ramesh, Suresh, Mahesh]


âœ… Here:

Each inner list â†’ converted to a Stream (Stream<String>)

flatMap() merges (flattens) all these inner streams into a single stream.

Difference Visually
Feature	map()	flatMap()
Mapping Type	One-to-One	One-to-Many
Output Type	Stream of values	Flattened Stream
Use Case	Transform elements	Flatten + transform elements
Example Input	["Atul", "Ramesh"]	[["Atul","Ramesh"], ["Suresh","Mahesh"]]
Example Output	[4, 6]	[Atul, Ramesh, Suresh, Mahesh]
ðŸ§© Practical Example: Extract words from a list of sentences
List<String> sentences = Arrays.asList("Java is powerful", "Streams are cool");

List<String> words = sentences.stream()
    .map(sentence -> sentence.split(" "))    // Stream<String[]>
    .flatMap(Arrays::stream)                 // Stream<String>
    .toList();

System.out.println(words);


Output:

[Java, is, powerful, Streams, are, cool]


map() â†’ gives Stream<String[]> (list of word arrays)

flatMap() â†’ merges all word arrays into a single Stream<String>

ðŸ§  In Short
Concept	map()	flatMap()
Input	Stream<T>	Stream<T>
Function Output	R	Stream<R>
Result	Stream<R>	Stream<R> (flattened)
Best Used For	Simple transformations	Nested collections or Streams of Streams
âœ… Summary Example
// map() Example
Stream.of("a", "b", "c")
      .map(String::toUpperCase)
      .forEach(System.out::println); // A, B, C

// flatMap() Example
Stream.of("Hello World", "Java Stream")
      .flatMap(s -> Arrays.stream(s.split(" ")))
      .forEach(System.out::println); // Hello, World, Java, Stream
